63 void Generate_JSBuiltinsConstructStubHelper(MacroAssembler* masm) {
64  // ----------- S t a t e -------------
65  // -- x0 : number of arguments
66  // -- x1 : constructor function
67  // -- x3 : new target
68  // -- cp : context
69  // -- lr : return address
70  // -- sp[...]: constructor arguments
71  // -----------------------------------
72 
73  ASM_LOCATION("Builtins::Generate_JSConstructStubHelper");
74  Label stack_overflow;
75 
76  __ StackOverflowCheck(x0, &stack_overflow);
77 
78  // Enter a construct frame.
79  {
80  FrameScope scope(masm, StackFrame::CONSTRUCT);
81  Label already_aligned;
82  Register argc = x0;
83 
84  if (v8_flags.debug_code) {
85  // Check that FrameScope pushed the context on to the stack already.
86  __ Peek(x2, 0);
87  __ Cmp(x2, cp);
88  __ Check(eq, AbortReason::kUnexpectedValue);
89  }
90 
91  // Push number of arguments.
92  __ Push(argc, padreg);
93 
94  // Round up to maintain alignment.
95  Register slot_count = x2;
96  Register slot_count_without_rounding = x12;
97  __ Add(slot_count_without_rounding, argc, 1);
98  __ Bic(slot_count, slot_count_without_rounding, 1);
99  __ Claim(slot_count);
100 
101  // Preserve the incoming parameters on the stack.
102  __ LoadRoot(x4, RootIndex::kTheHoleValue);
103 
104  // Compute a pointer to the slot immediately above the location on the
105  // stack to which arguments will be later copied.
106  __ SlotAddress(x2, argc);
107 
108  // Store padding, if needed.
109  __ Tbnz(slot_count_without_rounding, 0, &already_aligned);
110  __ Str(padreg, MemOperand(x2));
111  __ Bind(&already_aligned);
112 
113  // TODO(victorgomes): When the arguments adaptor is completely removed, we
114  // should get the formal parameter count and copy the arguments in its
115  // correct position (including any undefined), instead of delaying this to
116  // InvokeFunction.
117 
118  // Copy arguments to the expression stack.
119  {
120  Register count = x2;
121  Register dst = x10;
122  Register src = x11;
123  __ SlotAddress(dst, 0);
124  // Poke the hole (receiver).
125  __ Str(x4, MemOperand(dst));
126  __ Add(dst, dst, kSystemPointerSize); // Skip receiver.
127  __ Add(src, fp,
128  StandardFrameConstants::kCallerSPOffset +
129  kSystemPointerSize); // Skip receiver.
130  __ Sub(count, argc, kJSArgcReceiverSlots);
131  __ CopyDoubleWords(dst, src, count);
132  }
133 
134  // ----------- S t a t e -------------
135  // -- x0: number of arguments (untagged)
136  // -- x1: constructor function
137  // -- x3: new target
138  // If argc is odd:
139  // -- sp[0*kSystemPointerSize]: the hole (receiver)
140  // -- sp[1*kSystemPointerSize]: argument 1
141  // -- ...
142  // -- sp[(n-1)*kSystemPointerSize]: argument (n - 1)
143  // -- sp[(n+0)*kSystemPointerSize]: argument n
144  // -- sp[(n+1)*kSystemPointerSize]: padding
145  // -- sp[(n+2)*kSystemPointerSize]: padding
146  // -- sp[(n+3)*kSystemPointerSize]: number of arguments
147  // -- sp[(n+4)*kSystemPointerSize]: context (pushed by FrameScope)
148  // If argc is even:
149  // -- sp[0*kSystemPointerSize]: the hole (receiver)
150  // -- sp[1*kSystemPointerSize]: argument 1
151  // -- ...
152  // -- sp[(n-1)*kSystemPointerSize]: argument (n - 1)
153  // -- sp[(n+0)*kSystemPointerSize]: argument n
154  // -- sp[(n+1)*kSystemPointerSize]: padding
155  // -- sp[(n+2)*kSystemPointerSize]: number of arguments
156  // -- sp[(n+3)*kSystemPointerSize]: context (pushed by FrameScope)
157  // -----------------------------------
158 
159  // Call the function.
160  __ InvokeFunctionWithNewTarget(x1, x3, argc, InvokeType::kCall);
161 
162  // Restore the context from the frame.
163  __ Ldr(cp, MemOperand(fp, ConstructFrameConstants::kContextOffset));
164  // Restore arguments count from the frame. Use fp relative
165  // addressing to avoid the circular dependency between padding existence and
166  // argc parity.
167  __ Ldr(x1, MemOperand(fp, ConstructFrameConstants::kLengthOffset));
168  // Leave construct frame.
169  }
170 
171  // Remove caller arguments from the stack and return.
172  __ DropArguments(x1);
173  __ Ret();
174 
175  __ Bind(&stack_overflow);
176  {
177  FrameScope scope(masm, StackFrame::INTERNAL);
178  __ CallRuntime(Runtime::kThrowStackOverflow);
179  __ Unreachable();
180  }
181 }

185 // The construct stub for ES5 constructor functions and ES6 class constructors.
186 void Builtins::Generate_JSConstructStubGeneric(MacroAssembler* masm) {
187  // ----------- S t a t e -------------
188  // -- x0 : number of arguments
189  // -- x1 : constructor function
190  // -- x3 : new target
191  // -- lr : return address
192  // -- cp : context pointer
193  // -- sp[...]: constructor arguments
194  // -----------------------------------
195 
196  ASM_LOCATION("Builtins::Generate_JSConstructStubGeneric");
197 
198  FrameScope scope(masm, StackFrame::MANUAL);
199  // Enter a construct frame.
200  __ EnterFrame(StackFrame::CONSTRUCT);
201  Label post_instantiation_deopt_entry, not_create_implicit_receiver;
202 
203  if (v8_flags.debug_code) {
204  // Check that FrameScope pushed the context on to the stack already.
205  __ Peek(x2, 0);
206  __ Cmp(x2, cp);
207  __ Check(eq, AbortReason::kUnexpectedValue);
208  }
209 
210  // Preserve the incoming parameters on the stack.
211  __ Push(x0, x1, padreg, x3);
212 
213  // ----------- S t a t e -------------
214  // -- sp[0*kSystemPointerSize]: new target
215  // -- sp[1*kSystemPointerSize]: padding
216  // -- x1 and sp[2*kSystemPointerSize]: constructor function
217  // -- sp[3*kSystemPointerSize]: number of arguments
218  // -- sp[4*kSystemPointerSize]: context (pushed by FrameScope)
219  // -----------------------------------
220 
221  __ LoadTaggedField(
222  x4, FieldMemOperand(x1, JSFunction::kSharedFunctionInfoOffset));
223  __ Ldr(w4, FieldMemOperand(x4, SharedFunctionInfo::kFlagsOffset));
224  __ DecodeField<SharedFunctionInfo::FunctionKindBits>(w4);
225  __ JumpIfIsInRange(
226  w4, static_cast<uint32_t>(FunctionKind::kDefaultDerivedConstructor),
227  static_cast<uint32_t>(FunctionKind::kDerivedConstructor),
228  &not_create_implicit_receiver);
229 
230  // If not derived class constructor: Allocate the new receiver object.
231  __ CallBuiltin(Builtin::kFastNewObject);
232 
233  __ B(&post_instantiation_deopt_entry);
234 
235  // Else: use TheHoleValue as receiver for constructor call
236  __ Bind(&not_create_implicit_receiver);
237  __ LoadRoot(x0, RootIndex::kTheHoleValue);
238 
239  // ----------- S t a t e -------------
240  // -- x0: receiver
241  // -- Slot 4 / sp[0*kSystemPointerSize]: new target
242  // -- Slot 3 / sp[1*kSystemPointerSize]: padding
243  // -- Slot 2 / sp[2*kSystemPointerSize]: constructor function
244  // -- Slot 1 / sp[3*kSystemPointerSize]: number of arguments
245  // -- Slot 0 / sp[4*kSystemPointerSize]: context
246  // -----------------------------------
247  // Deoptimizer enters here.
248  masm->isolate()->heap()->SetConstructStubCreateDeoptPCOffset(
249  masm->pc_offset());
250 
251  __ Bind(&post_instantiation_deopt_entry);
252 
253  // Restore new target from the top of the stack.
254  __ Peek(x3, 0 * kSystemPointerSize);
255 
256  // Restore constructor function and argument count.
257  __ Ldr(x1, MemOperand(fp, ConstructFrameConstants::kConstructorOffset));
258  __ Ldr(x12, MemOperand(fp, ConstructFrameConstants::kLengthOffset));
259 
260  // Copy arguments to the expression stack. The called function pops the
261  // receiver along with its arguments, so we need an extra receiver on the
262  // stack, in case we have to return it later.
263 
264  // Overwrite the new target with a receiver.
265  __ Poke(x0, 0);
266 
267  // Push two further copies of the receiver. One will be popped by the called
268  // function. The second acts as padding if the number of arguments plus
269  // receiver is odd - pushing receiver twice avoids branching. It also means
270  // that we don't have to handle the even and odd cases specially on
271  // InvokeFunction's return, as top of stack will be the receiver in either
272  // case.
273  __ Push(x0, x0);
274 
275  // ----------- S t a t e -------------
276  // -- x3: new target
277  // -- x12: number of arguments (untagged)
278  // -- sp[0*kSystemPointerSize]: implicit receiver (overwrite if argc
279  // odd)
280  // -- sp[1*kSystemPointerSize]: implicit receiver
281  // -- sp[2*kSystemPointerSize]: implicit receiver
282  // -- sp[3*kSystemPointerSize]: padding
283  // -- x1 and sp[4*kSystemPointerSize]: constructor function
284  // -- sp[5*kSystemPointerSize]: number of arguments
285  // -- sp[6*kSystemPointerSize]: context
286  // -----------------------------------
287 
288  // Round the number of arguments down to the next even number, and claim
289  // slots for the arguments. If the number of arguments was odd, the last
290  // argument will overwrite one of the receivers pushed above.
291  Register argc_without_receiver = x11;
292  __ Sub(argc_without_receiver, x12, kJSArgcReceiverSlots);
293  __ Bic(x10, x12, 1);
294 
295  // Check if we have enough stack space to push all arguments.
296  Label stack_overflow;
297  __ StackOverflowCheck(x10, &stack_overflow);
298  __ Claim(x10);
299 
300  // TODO(victorgomes): When the arguments adaptor is completely removed, we
301  // should get the formal parameter count and copy the arguments in its
302  // correct position (including any undefined), instead of delaying this to
303  // InvokeFunction.
304 
305  // Copy the arguments.
306  {
307  Register count = x2;
308  Register dst = x10;
309  Register src = x11;
310  __ Mov(count, argc_without_receiver);
311  __ Poke(x0, 0); // Add the receiver.
312  __ SlotAddress(dst, 1); // Skip receiver.
313  __ Add(src, fp,
314  StandardFrameConstants::kCallerSPOffset + kSystemPointerSize);
315  __ CopyDoubleWords(dst, src, count);
316  }
317 
318  // Call the function.
319  __ Mov(x0, x12);
320  __ InvokeFunctionWithNewTarget(x1, x3, x0, InvokeType::kCall);
321 
322  // If the result is an object (in the ECMA sense), we should get rid
323  // of the receiver and use the result; see ECMA-262 section 13.2.2-7
324  // on page 74.
325  Label use_receiver, do_throw, leave_and_return, check_receiver;
326 
327  // If the result is undefined, we jump out to using the implicit receiver.
328  __ CompareRoot(x0, RootIndex::kUndefinedValue);
329  __ B(ne, &check_receiver);
330 
331  // Throw away the result of the constructor invocation and use the
332  // on-stack receiver as the result.
333  __ Bind(&use_receiver);
334  __ Peek(x0, 0 * kSystemPointerSize);
335  __ CompareRoot(x0, RootIndex::kTheHoleValue);
336  __ B(eq, &do_throw);
337 
338  __ Bind(&leave_and_return);
339  // Restore arguments count from the frame.
340  __ Ldr(x1, MemOperand(fp, ConstructFrameConstants::kLengthOffset));
341  // Leave construct frame.
342  __ LeaveFrame(StackFrame::CONSTRUCT);
343  // Remove caller arguments from the stack and return.
344  __ DropArguments(x1);
345  __ Ret();
346 
347  // Otherwise we do a smi check and fall through to check if the return value
348  // is a valid receiver.
349  __ bind(&check_receiver);
350 
351  // If the result is a smi, it is *not* an object in the ECMA sense.
352  __ JumpIfSmi(x0, &use_receiver);
353 
354  // Check if the type of the result is not an object in the ECMA sense.
355  __ JumpIfJSAnyIsNotPrimitive(x0, x4, &leave_and_return);
356  __ B(&use_receiver);
357 
358  __ Bind(&do_throw);
359  // Restore the context from the frame.
360  __ Ldr(cp, MemOperand(fp, ConstructFrameConstants::kContextOffset));
361  __ CallRuntime(Runtime::kThrowConstructorReturnedNonObject);
362  __ Unreachable();
363 
364  __ Bind(&stack_overflow);
365  // Restore the context from the frame.
366  __ Ldr(cp, MemOperand(fp, ConstructFrameConstants::kContextOffset));
367  __ CallRuntime(Runtime::kThrowStackOverflow);
368  __ Unreachable();
369 }

381 static void AssertCodeIsBaselineAllowClobber(MacroAssembler* masm,
382  Register code, Register scratch) {
383  // Verify that the code kind is baseline code via the CodeKind.
384  __ Ldr(scratch, FieldMemOperand(code, Code::kFlagsOffset));
385  __ DecodeField<Code::KindField>(scratch);
386  __ Cmp(scratch, Operand(static_cast<int>(CodeKind::BASELINE)));
387  __ Assert(eq, AbortReason::kExpectedBaselineData);
388 }
389 
390 static void AssertCodeIsBaseline(MacroAssembler* masm, Register code,
391  Register scratch) {
392  DCHECK(!AreAliased(code, scratch));
393  return AssertCodeIsBaselineAllowClobber(masm, code, scratch);
394 }

396 static void CheckSharedFunctionInfoBytecodeOrBaseline(MacroAssembler* masm,
397  Register data,
398  Register scratch,
399  Label* is_baseline,
400  Label* is_bytecode) {
401 #if V8_STATIC_ROOTS_BOOL
402  __ IsObjectTypeFast(data, scratch, CODE_TYPE);
403 #else
404  __ CompareObjectType(data, scratch, scratch, CODE_TYPE);
405 #endif // V8_STATIC_ROOTS_BOOL
406  if (v8_flags.debug_code) {
407  Label not_baseline;
408  __ B(ne, &not_baseline);
409  AssertCodeIsBaseline(masm, data, scratch);
410  __ B(eq, is_baseline);
411  __ Bind(&not_baseline);
412  } else {
413  __ B(eq, is_baseline);
414  }
415 
416 #if V8_STATIC_ROOTS_BOOL
417  // scratch already contains the compressed map.
418  __ CompareInstanceTypeWithUniqueCompressedMap(scratch, Register::no_reg(),
419  INTERPRETER_DATA_TYPE);
420 #else
421  // scratch already contains the instance type.
422  __ Cmp(scratch, INTERPRETER_DATA_TYPE);
423 #endif // V8_STATIC_ROOTS_BOOL
424  __ B(ne, is_bytecode);
425 }

427 // TODO(v8:11429): Add a path for "not_compiled" and unify the two uses under
428 // the more general dispatch.
429 static void GetSharedFunctionInfoBytecodeOrBaseline(
430  MacroAssembler* masm, Register sfi, Register bytecode, Register scratch1,
431  Label* is_baseline, Label* is_unavailable) {
432  DCHECK(!AreAliased(bytecode, scratch1));
433  ASM_CODE_COMMENT(masm);
434  Label done;
435 
436  Register data = bytecode;
437  __ LoadTrustedPointerField(
438  data,
439  FieldMemOperand(sfi, SharedFunctionInfo::kTrustedFunctionDataOffset),
440  kUnknownIndirectPointerTag);
441 
442  if (V8_JITLESS_BOOL) {
443  __ IsObjectType(data, scratch1, scratch1, INTERPRETER_DATA_TYPE);
444  __ B(ne, &done);
445  } else {
446  CheckSharedFunctionInfoBytecodeOrBaseline(masm, data, scratch1, is_baseline,
447  &done);
448  }
449 
450  __ LoadProtectedPointerField(
451  bytecode, FieldMemOperand(data, InterpreterData::kBytecodeArrayOffset));
452 
453  __ Bind(&done);
454  __ IsObjectType(bytecode, scratch1, scratch1, BYTECODE_ARRAY_TYPE);
455  __ B(ne, is_unavailable);
456 }

458 // static
459 void Builtins::Generate_ResumeGeneratorTrampoline(MacroAssembler* masm) {
460  // ----------- S t a t e -------------
461  // -- x0 : the value to pass to the generator
462  // -- x1 : the JSGeneratorObject to resume
463  // -- lr : return address
464  // -----------------------------------
465 
466  // Store input value into generator object.
467  __ StoreTaggedField(
468  x0, FieldMemOperand(x1, JSGeneratorObject::kInputOrDebugPosOffset));
469  __ RecordWriteField(x1, JSGeneratorObject::kInputOrDebugPosOffset, x0,
470  kLRHasNotBeenSaved, SaveFPRegsMode::kIgnore);
471  // Check that x1 is still valid, RecordWrite might have clobbered it.
472  __ AssertGeneratorObject(x1);
473 
474  // Load suspended function and context.
475  __ LoadTaggedField(x5,
476  FieldMemOperand(x1, JSGeneratorObject::kFunctionOffset));
477  __ LoadTaggedField(cp, FieldMemOperand(x5, JSFunction::kContextOffset));
478 
479  // Flood function if we are stepping.
480  Label prepare_step_in_if_stepping, prepare_step_in_suspended_generator;
481  Label stepping_prepared;
482  ExternalReference debug_hook =
483  ExternalReference::debug_hook_on_function_call_address(masm->isolate());
484  __ Mov(x10, debug_hook);
485  __ Ldrsb(x10, MemOperand(x10));
486  __ CompareAndBranch(x10, Operand(0), ne, &prepare_step_in_if_stepping);
487 
488  // Flood function if we need to continue stepping in the suspended generator.
489  ExternalReference debug_suspended_generator =
490  ExternalReference::debug_suspended_generator_address(masm->isolate());
491  __ Mov(x10, debug_suspended_generator);
492  __ Ldr(x10, MemOperand(x10));
493  __ CompareAndBranch(x10, Operand(x1), eq,
494  &prepare_step_in_suspended_generator);
495  __ Bind(&stepping_prepared);
496 
497  // Check the stack for overflow. We are not trying to catch interruptions
498  // (i.e. debug break and preemption) here, so check the "real stack limit".
499  Label stack_overflow;
500  __ LoadStackLimit(x10, StackLimitKind::kRealStackLimit);
501  __ Cmp(sp, x10);
502  __ B(lo, &stack_overflow);
503 
504  Register argc = kJavaScriptCallArgCountRegister;
505 
506  // Compute actual arguments count value as a formal parameter count without
507  // receiver, loaded from the dispatch table entry or shared function info.
508 #if V8_ENABLE_LEAPTIERING
509  Register dispatch_handle = kJavaScriptCallDispatchHandleRegister;
510  Register code = kJavaScriptCallCodeStartRegister;
511  Register scratch = x20;
512  __ Ldr(dispatch_handle.W(),
513  FieldMemOperand(x5, JSFunction::kDispatchHandleOffset));
514  __ LoadEntrypointAndParameterCountFromJSDispatchTable(
515  code, argc, dispatch_handle, scratch);
516 
517  // In case the formal parameter count is kDontAdaptArgumentsSentinel the
518  // actual arguments count should be set accordingly.
519  static_assert(kDontAdaptArgumentsSentinel < JSParameterCount(0));
520  __ Cmp(argc, Operand(JSParameterCount(0)));
521  __ Csel(argc, argc, Operand(JSParameterCount(0)), kGreaterThan);
522 #else
523  __ LoadTaggedField(
524  argc, FieldMemOperand(x5, JSFunction::kSharedFunctionInfoOffset));
525  __ Ldrh(argc.W(), FieldMemOperand(
526  argc, SharedFunctionInfo::kFormalParameterCountOffset));
527 
528  // Generator functions are always created from user code and thus the
529  // formal parameter count is never equal to kDontAdaptArgumentsSentinel,
530  // which is used only for certain non-generator builtin functions.
531 #endif // V8_ENABLE_LEAPTIERING
532 
533  // Claim slots for arguments and receiver (rounded up to a multiple of two).
534  static_assert(JSParameterCount(0) == 1); // argc includes receiver
535  __ Add(x11, argc, 1);
536  __ Bic(x11, x11, 1);
537  __ Claim(x11);
538 
539  // Store padding (which might be replaced by the last argument).
540  __ Sub(x11, x11, 1);
541  __ Poke(padreg, Operand(x11, LSL, kSystemPointerSizeLog2));
542 
543  // Poke receiver into highest claimed slot.
544  __ LoadTaggedField(x6,
545  FieldMemOperand(x1, JSGeneratorObject::kReceiverOffset));
546  __ Poke(x6, __ ReceiverOperand());
547 
548  // ----------- S t a t e -------------
549  // -- x0 : actual arguments count
550  // -- x1 : the JSGeneratorObject to resume
551  // -- x2 : target code object (leaptiering only)
552  // -- x4 : dispatch handle (leaptiering only)
553  // -- x5 : generator function
554  // -- cp : generator context
555  // -- lr : return address
556  // -- sp[0 .. arg count] : claimed for receiver and args
557  // -----------------------------------
558 
559  // Copy the function arguments from the generator object's register file.
560  {
561  Label loop, done;
562  __ Sub(x10, argc, kJSArgcReceiverSlots);
563  __ Cbz(x10, &done);
564  __ LoadTaggedField(
565  x6,
566  FieldMemOperand(x1, JSGeneratorObject::kParametersAndRegistersOffset));
567 
568  __ SlotAddress(x12, x10);
569  __ Add(x6, x6, Operand(x10, LSL, kTaggedSizeLog2));
570  __ Add(x6, x6, Operand(OFFSET_OF_DATA_START(FixedArray) - kHeapObjectTag));
571  __ Bind(&loop);
572  __ Sub(x10, x10, 1);
573  __ LoadTaggedField(x11, MemOperand(x6, -kTaggedSize, PreIndex));
574  __ Str(x11, MemOperand(x12, -kSystemPointerSize, PostIndex));
575  __ Cbnz(x10, &loop);
576  __ Bind(&done);
577  }
578 
579  // Underlying function needs to have bytecode available.
580  if (v8_flags.debug_code) {
581  Label ok, is_baseline, is_unavailable;
582  Register sfi = x10;
583  Register bytecode = x10;
584  Register scratch = x11;
585  __ LoadTaggedField(
586  sfi, FieldMemOperand(x5, JSFunction::kSharedFunctionInfoOffset));
587  GetSharedFunctionInfoBytecodeOrBaseline(masm, sfi, bytecode, scratch,
588  &is_baseline, &is_unavailable);
589  __ B(&ok);
590 
591  __ Bind(&is_unavailable);
592  __ Abort(AbortReason::kMissingBytecodeArray);
593 
594  __ Bind(&is_baseline);
595  __ IsObjectType(bytecode, scratch, scratch, CODE_TYPE);
596  __ Assert(eq, AbortReason::kMissingBytecodeArray);
597 
598  __ Bind(&ok);
599  }
600 
601  // Resume (Ignition/TurboFan) generator object.
602  {
603  // We abuse new.target both to indicate that this is a resume call and to
604  // pass in the generator object. In ordinary calls, new.target is always
605  // undefined because generator functions are non-constructable.
606  __ Mov(x3, x1); // new.target
607  __ Mov(x1, x5); // target
608 #if V8_ENABLE_LEAPTIERING
609  // We jump through x17 here because for Branch Identification (BTI) we use
610  // "Call" (`bti c`) rather than "Jump" (`bti j`) landing pads for
611  // tail-called code. See TailCallBuiltin for more information.
612  DCHECK_NE(code, x17);
613  __ Mov(x17, code);
614  // Actual arguments count and code start are already initialized above.
615  __ Jump(x17);
616 #else
617  // Actual arguments count is already initialized above.
618  __ JumpJSFunction(x1);
619 #endif // V8_ENABLE_LEAPTIERING
620  }
621 
622  __ Bind(&prepare_step_in_if_stepping);
623  {
624  FrameScope scope(masm, StackFrame::INTERNAL);
625  // Push hole as receiver since we do not use it for stepping.
626  __ LoadRoot(x6, RootIndex::kTheHoleValue);
627  __ Push(x1, padreg, x5, x6);
628  __ CallRuntime(Runtime::kDebugOnFunctionCall);
629  __ Pop(padreg, x1);
630  __ LoadTaggedField(x5,
631  FieldMemOperand(x1, JSGeneratorObject::kFunctionOffset));
632  }
633  __ B(&stepping_prepared);
634 
635  __ Bind(&prepare_step_in_suspended_generator);
636  {
637  FrameScope scope(masm, StackFrame::INTERNAL);
638  __ Push(x1, padreg);
639  __ CallRuntime(Runtime::kDebugPrepareStepInSuspendedGenerator);
640  __ Pop(padreg, x1);
641  __ LoadTaggedField(x5,
642  FieldMemOperand(x1, JSGeneratorObject::kFunctionOffset));
643  }
644  __ B(&stepping_prepared);
645 
646  __ bind(&stack_overflow);
647  {
648  FrameScope scope(masm, StackFrame::INTERNAL);
649  __ CallRuntime(Runtime::kThrowStackOverflow);
650  __ Unreachable(); // This should be unreachable.
651  }
652 }

654 namespace {
655 
656 // Called with the native C calling convention. The corresponding function
657 // signature is either:
658 //
659 // using JSEntryFunction = GeneratedCode<Address(
660 // Address root_register_value, Address new_target, Address target,
661 // Address receiver, intptr_t argc, Address** argv)>;
662 // or
663 // using JSEntryFunction = GeneratedCode<Address(
664 // Address root_register_value, MicrotaskQueue* microtask_queue)>;
665 //
666 // Input is either:
667 // x0: root_register_value.
668 // x1: new_target.
669 // x2: target.
670 // x3: receiver.
671 // x4: argc.
672 // x5: argv.
673 // or
674 // x0: root_register_value.
675 // x1: microtask_queue.
676 // Output:
677 // x0: result.
678 void Generate_JSEntryVariant(MacroAssembler* masm, StackFrame::Type type,
679  Builtin entry_trampoline) {
680  Label invoke, handler_entry, exit;
681 
682  {
683  NoRootArrayScope no_root_array(masm);
684 
685 #if defined(V8_OS_WIN)
686  // In order to allow Windows debugging tools to reconstruct a call stack, we
687  // must generate information describing how to recover at least fp, sp, and
688  // pc for the calling frame. Here, JSEntry registers offsets to
689  // xdata_encoder which then emits the offset values as part of the unwind
690  // data accordingly.
691  win64_unwindinfo::XdataEncoder* xdata_encoder = masm->GetXdataEncoder();
692  if (xdata_encoder) {
693  xdata_encoder->onFramePointerAdjustment(
694  EntryFrameConstants::kDirectCallerFPOffset,
695  EntryFrameConstants::kDirectCallerSPOffset);
696  }
697 #endif
698 
699  __ PushCalleeSavedRegisters();
700 
701  // Set up the reserved register for 0.0.
702  __ Fmov(fp_zero, 0.0);
703 
704  // Initialize the root register.
705  // C calling convention. The first argument is passed in x0.
706  __ Mov(kRootRegister, x0);
707 
708 #ifdef V8_COMPRESS_POINTERS
709  // Initialize the pointer cage base register.
710  __ LoadRootRelative(kPtrComprCageBaseRegister,
711  IsolateData::cage_base_offset());
712 #endif
713  }
714 
715  // Set up fp. It points to the {fp, lr} pair pushed as the last step in
716  // PushCalleeSavedRegisters.
717  static_assert(
718  EntryFrameConstants::kCalleeSavedRegisterBytesPushedAfterFpLrPair == 0);
719  static_assert(EntryFrameConstants::kOffsetToCalleeSavedRegisters == 0);
720  __ Mov(fp, sp);
721 
722  // Build an entry frame (see layout below).
723 
724  // Push frame type markers.
725  __ Mov(x12, StackFrame::TypeToMarker(type));
726  __ Push(x12, xzr);
727 
728  __ Mov(x11, ExternalReference::Create(IsolateAddressId::kCEntryFPAddress,
729  masm->isolate()));
730  __ Ldr(x10, MemOperand(x11)); // x10 = C entry FP.
731 
732  // Clear c_entry_fp, now we've loaded its value to be pushed on the stack.
733  // If the c_entry_fp is not already zero and we don't clear it, the
734  // StackFrameIteratorForProfiler will assume we are executing C++ and miss the
735  // JS frames on top.
736  __ Str(xzr, MemOperand(x11));
737 
738  // Set js_entry_sp if this is the outermost JS call.
739  Label done;
740  ExternalReference js_entry_sp = ExternalReference::Create(
741  IsolateAddressId::kJSEntrySPAddress, masm->isolate());
742  __ Mov(x12, js_entry_sp);
743  __ Ldr(x11, MemOperand(x12)); // x11 = previous JS entry SP.
744 
745  // Select between the inner and outermost frame marker, based on the JS entry
746  // sp. We assert that the inner marker is zero, so we can use xzr to save a
747  // move instruction.
748  DCHECK_EQ(StackFrame::INNER_JSENTRY_FRAME, 0);
749  __ Cmp(x11, 0); // If x11 is zero, this is the outermost frame.
750  // x11 = JS entry frame marker.
751  __ Csel(x11, xzr, StackFrame::OUTERMOST_JSENTRY_FRAME, ne);
752  __ B(ne, &done);
753  __ Str(fp, MemOperand(x12));
754 
755  __ Bind(&done);
756 
757  __ LoadIsolateField(x9, IsolateFieldId::kFastCCallCallerFP);
758  __ Ldr(x7, MemOperand(x9));
759  __ Str(xzr, MemOperand(x9));
760  __ LoadIsolateField(x9, IsolateFieldId::kFastCCallCallerPC);
761  __ Ldr(x8, MemOperand(x9));
762  __ Str(xzr, MemOperand(x9));
763  __ Push(x10, x11, x7, x8);
764 
765  // The frame set up looks like this:
766  // sp[0] : fast api call pc.
767  // sp[1] : fast api call fp.
768  // sp[2] : JS entry frame marker.
769  // sp[3] : C entry FP.
770  // sp[4] : stack frame marker (0).
771  // sp[5] : stack frame marker (type).
772  // sp[6] : saved fp <- fp points here.
773  // sp[7] : saved lr
774  // sp[8,26) : other saved registers
775 
776  // Jump to a faked try block that does the invoke, with a faked catch
777  // block that sets the exception.
778  __ B(&invoke);
779 
780  // Prevent the constant pool from being emitted between the record of the
781  // handler_entry position and the first instruction of the sequence here.
782  // There is no risk because Assembler::Emit() emits the instruction before
783  // checking for constant pool emission, but we do not want to depend on
784  // that.
785  {
786  Assembler::BlockPoolsScope block_pools(masm);
787 
788  // Store the current pc as the handler offset. It's used later to create the
789  // handler table.
790  __ BindExceptionHandler(&handler_entry);
791  masm->isolate()->builtins()->SetJSEntryHandlerOffset(handler_entry.pos());
792 
793  // Caught exception: Store result (exception) in the exception
794  // field in the JSEnv and return a failure sentinel. Coming in here the
795  // fp will be invalid because UnwindAndFindHandler sets it to 0 to
796  // signal the existence of the JSEntry frame.
797  __ Mov(x10, ExternalReference::Create(IsolateAddressId::kExceptionAddress,
798  masm->isolate()));
799  }
800  __ Str(x0, MemOperand(x10));
801  __ LoadRoot(x0, RootIndex::kException);
802  __ B(&exit);
803 
804  // Invoke: Link this frame into the handler chain.
805  __ Bind(&invoke);
806 
807  // Push new stack handler.
808  static_assert(StackHandlerConstants::kSize == 2 * kSystemPointerSize,
809  "Unexpected offset for StackHandlerConstants::kSize");
810  static_assert(StackHandlerConstants::kNextOffset == 0 * kSystemPointerSize,
811  "Unexpected offset for StackHandlerConstants::kNextOffset");
812 
813  // Link the current handler as the next handler.
814  __ Mov(x11, ExternalReference::Create(IsolateAddressId::kHandlerAddress,
815  masm->isolate()));
816  __ Ldr(x10, MemOperand(x11));
817  __ Push(padreg, x10);
818 
819  // Set this new handler as the current one.
820  {
821  UseScratchRegisterScope temps(masm);
822  Register scratch = temps.AcquireX();
823  __ Mov(scratch, sp);
824  __ Str(scratch, MemOperand(x11));
825  }
826 
827  // If an exception not caught by another handler occurs, this handler
828  // returns control to the code after the B(&invoke) above, which
829  // restores all callee-saved registers (including cp and fp) to their
830  // saved values before returning a failure to C.
831  //
832  // Invoke the function by calling through JS entry trampoline builtin and
833  // pop the faked function when we return.
834  __ CallBuiltin(entry_trampoline);
835 
836  // Pop the stack handler and unlink this frame from the handler chain.
837  static_assert(StackHandlerConstants::kNextOffset == 0 * kSystemPointerSize,
838  "Unexpected offset for StackHandlerConstants::kNextOffset");
839  __ Pop(x10, padreg);
840  __ Mov(x11, ExternalReference::Create(IsolateAddressId::kHandlerAddress,
841  masm->isolate()));
842  __ Drop(StackHandlerConstants::kSlotCount - 2);
843  __ Str(x10, MemOperand(x11));
844 
845  __ Bind(&exit);
846  // x0 holds the result.
847  // The stack pointer points to the top of the entry frame pushed on entry from
848  // C++ (at the beginning of this stub):
849  // sp[0] : fast api call pc.
850  // sp[1] : fast api call fp.
851  // sp[2] : JS entry frame marker.
852  // sp[3] : C entry FP.
853  // sp[4] : stack frame marker (0).
854  // sp[5] : stack frame marker (type).
855  // sp[6] : saved fp <- fp points here.
856  // sp[7] : saved lr
857  // sp[8,26) : other saved registers
858 
859  __ Pop(x10, x11);
860  __ LoadIsolateField(x8, IsolateFieldId::kFastCCallCallerPC);
861  __ Str(x10, MemOperand(x8));
862  __ LoadIsolateField(x9, IsolateFieldId::kFastCCallCallerFP);
863  __ Str(x11, MemOperand(x9));
864 
865  // Check if the current stack frame is marked as the outermost JS frame.
866  Label non_outermost_js_2;
867  {
868  Register c_entry_fp = x11;
869  __ PeekPair(x10, c_entry_fp, 0);
870  __ Cmp(x10, StackFrame::OUTERMOST_JSENTRY_FRAME);
871  __ B(ne, &non_outermost_js_2);
872  __ Mov(x12, js_entry_sp);
873  __ Str(xzr, MemOperand(x12));
874  __ Bind(&non_outermost_js_2);
875 
876  // Restore the top frame descriptors from the stack.
877  __ Mov(x12, ExternalReference::Create(IsolateAddressId::kCEntryFPAddress,
878  masm->isolate()));
879  __ Str(c_entry_fp, MemOperand(x12));
880  }
881 
882  // Reset the stack to the callee saved registers.
883  static_assert(
884  EntryFrameConstants::kFixedFrameSize % (2 * kSystemPointerSize) == 0,
885  "Size of entry frame is not a multiple of 16 bytes");
886  // fast_c_call_caller_fp and fast_c_call_caller_pc have already been popped.
887  int drop_count =
888  (EntryFrameConstants::kFixedFrameSize / kSystemPointerSize) - 2;
889  __ Drop(drop_count);
890  // Restore the callee-saved registers and return.
891  __ PopCalleeSavedRegisters();
892  __ Ret();
893 }

911 // Input:
912 // x1: new.target.
913 // x2: function.
914 // x3: receiver.
915 // x4: argc.
916 // x5: argv.
917 // Output:
918 // x0: result.
919 static void Generate_JSEntryTrampolineHelper(MacroAssembler* masm,
920  bool is_construct) {
921  Register new_target = x1;
922  Register function = x2;
923  Register receiver = x3;
924  Register argc = x4;
925  Register argv = x5;
926  Register scratch = x10;
927  Register slots_to_claim = x11;
928 
929  {
930  // Enter an internal frame.
931  FrameScope scope(masm, StackFrame::INTERNAL);
932 
933  // Setup the context (we need to use the caller context from the isolate).
934  __ Mov(scratch, ExternalReference::Create(IsolateAddressId::kContextAddress,
935  masm->isolate()));
936  __ Ldr(cp, MemOperand(scratch));
937 #ifdef DEBUG
938  Register no_context = x9;
939  __ Mov(no_context, Operand(Context::kNoContext));
940  __ Str(no_context, MemOperand(scratch));
941 #endif
942 
943  // Claim enough space for the arguments and the function, including an
944  // optional slot of padding.
945  constexpr int additional_slots = 2;
946  __ Add(slots_to_claim, argc, additional_slots);
947  __ Bic(slots_to_claim, slots_to_claim, 1);
948 
949  // Check if we have enough stack space to push all arguments.
950  Label enough_stack_space, stack_overflow;
951  __ StackOverflowCheck(slots_to_claim, &stack_overflow);
952  __ B(&enough_stack_space);
953 
954  __ Bind(&stack_overflow);
955  __ CallRuntime(Runtime::kThrowStackOverflow);
956  __ Unreachable();
957 
958  __ Bind(&enough_stack_space);
959  __ Claim(slots_to_claim);
960 
961  // Store padding (which might be overwritten).
962  __ SlotAddress(scratch, slots_to_claim);
963  __ Str(padreg, MemOperand(scratch, -kSystemPointerSize));
964 
965  // Store receiver on the stack.
966  __ Poke(receiver, 0);
967  // Store function on the stack.
968  __ SlotAddress(scratch, argc);
969  __ Str(function, MemOperand(scratch));
970 
971  // Copy arguments to the stack in a loop, in reverse order.
972  // x4: argc.
973  // x5: argv.
974  Label loop, done;
975 
976  // Skip the argument set up if we have no arguments.
977  __ Cmp(argc, JSParameterCount(0));
978  __ B(eq, &done);
979 
980  // scratch has been set to point to the location of the function, which
981  // marks the end of the argument copy.
982  __ SlotAddress(x0, 1); // Skips receiver.
983  __ Bind(&loop);
984  // Load the handle.
985  __ Ldr(x11, MemOperand(argv, kSystemPointerSize, PostIndex));
986  // Dereference the handle.
987  __ Ldr(x11, MemOperand(x11));
988  // Poke the result into the stack.
989  __ Str(x11, MemOperand(x0, kSystemPointerSize, PostIndex));
990  // Loop if we've not reached the end of copy marker.
991  __ Cmp(x0, scratch);
992  __ B(lt, &loop);
993 
994  __ Bind(&done);
995 
996  __ Mov(x0, argc);
997  __ Mov(x3, new_target);
998  __ Mov(x1, function);
999  // x0: argc.
1000  // x1: function.
1001  // x3: new.target.
1002 
1003  // Initialize all JavaScript callee-saved registers, since they will be seen
1004  // by the garbage collector as part of handlers.
1005  // The original values have been saved in JSEntry.
1006  __ LoadRoot(x19, RootIndex::kUndefinedValue);
1007  __ Mov(x20, x19);
1008  __ Mov(x21, x19);
1009  __ Mov(x22, x19);
1010  __ Mov(x23, x19);
1011  __ Mov(x24, x19);
1012  __ Mov(x25, x19);
1013 #ifndef V8_COMPRESS_POINTERS
1014  __ Mov(x28, x19);
1015 #endif
1016  // Don't initialize the reserved registers.
1017  // x26 : root register (kRootRegister).
1018  // x27 : context pointer (cp).
1019  // x28 : pointer cage base register (kPtrComprCageBaseRegister).
1020  // x29 : frame pointer (fp).
1021 
1022  Builtin builtin = is_construct ? Builtin::kConstruct : Builtins::Call();
1023  __ CallBuiltin(builtin);
1024 
1025  // Exit the JS internal frame and remove the parameters (except function),
1026  // and return.
1027  }
1028 
1029  // Result is in x0. Return.
1030  __ Ret();
1031 }

1051 static void LeaveInterpreterFrame(MacroAssembler* masm, Register scratch1,
1052  Register scratch2) {
1053  ASM_CODE_COMMENT(masm);
1054  Register params_size = scratch1;
1055  // Get the size of the formal parameters + receiver (in bytes).
1056  __ Ldr(params_size,
1057  MemOperand(fp, InterpreterFrameConstants::kBytecodeArrayFromFp));
1058  __ Ldrh(params_size.W(),
1059  FieldMemOperand(params_size, BytecodeArray::kParameterSizeOffset));
1060 
1061  Register actual_params_size = scratch2;
1062  // Compute the size of the actual parameters + receiver (in bytes).
1063  __ Ldr(actual_params_size,
1064  MemOperand(fp, StandardFrameConstants::kArgCOffset));
1065 
1066  // If actual is bigger than formal, then we should use it to free up the stack
1067  // arguments.
1068  __ Cmp(params_size, actual_params_size);
1069  __ Csel(params_size, actual_params_size, params_size, kLessThan);
1070 
1071  // Leave the frame (also dropping the register file).
1072  __ LeaveFrame(StackFrame::INTERPRETED);
1073 
1074  // Drop receiver + arguments.
1075  __ DropArguments(params_size);
1076 }

1078 // Advance the current bytecode offset. This simulates what all bytecode
1079 // handlers do upon completion of the underlying operation. Will bail out to a
1080 // label if the bytecode (without prefix) is a return bytecode. Will not advance
1081 // the bytecode offset if the current bytecode is a JumpLoop, instead just
1082 // re-executing the JumpLoop to jump to the correct bytecode.
1083 static void AdvanceBytecodeOffsetOrReturn(MacroAssembler* masm,
1084  Register bytecode_array,
1085  Register bytecode_offset,
1086  Register bytecode, Register scratch1,
1087  Register scratch2, Label* if_return) {
1088  ASM_CODE_COMMENT(masm);
1089  Register bytecode_size_table = scratch1;
1090 
1091  // The bytecode offset value will be increased by one in wide and extra wide
1092  // cases. In the case of having a wide or extra wide JumpLoop bytecode, we
1093  // will restore the original bytecode. In order to simplify the code, we have
1094  // a backup of it.
1095  Register original_bytecode_offset = scratch2;
1096  DCHECK(!AreAliased(bytecode_array, bytecode_offset, bytecode_size_table,
1097  bytecode, original_bytecode_offset));
1098 
1099  __ Mov(bytecode_size_table, ExternalReference::bytecode_size_table_address());
1100  __ Mov(original_bytecode_offset, bytecode_offset);
1101 
1102  // Check if the bytecode is a Wide or ExtraWide prefix bytecode.
1103  Label process_bytecode, extra_wide;
1104  static_assert(0 == static_cast<int>(interpreter::Bytecode::kWide));
1105  static_assert(1 == static_cast<int>(interpreter::Bytecode::kExtraWide));
1106  static_assert(2 == static_cast<int>(interpreter::Bytecode::kDebugBreakWide));
1107  static_assert(3 ==
1108  static_cast<int>(interpreter::Bytecode::kDebugBreakExtraWide));
1109  __ Cmp(bytecode, Operand(0x3));
1110  __ B(hi, &process_bytecode);
1111  __ Tst(bytecode, Operand(0x1));
1112  // The code to load the next bytecode is common to both wide and extra wide.
1113  // We can hoist them up here since they do not modify the flags after Tst.
1114  __ Add(bytecode_offset, bytecode_offset, Operand(1));
1115  __ Ldrb(bytecode, MemOperand(bytecode_array, bytecode_offset));
1116  __ B(ne, &extra_wide);
1117 
1118  // Update table to the wide scaled table.
1119  __ Add(bytecode_size_table, bytecode_size_table,
1120  Operand(kByteSize * interpreter::Bytecodes::kBytecodeCount));
1121  __ B(&process_bytecode);
1122 
1123  __ Bind(&extra_wide);
1124  // Update table to the extra wide scaled table.
1125  __ Add(bytecode_size_table, bytecode_size_table,
1126  Operand(2 * kByteSize * interpreter::Bytecodes::kBytecodeCount));
1127 
1128  __ Bind(&process_bytecode);
1129 
1130 // Bailout to the return label if this is a return bytecode.
1131 #define JUMP_IF_EQUAL(NAME) \
1132  __ Cmp(x1, Operand(static_cast<int>(interpreter::Bytecode::k##NAME))); \
1133  __ B(if_return, eq);
1134  RETURN_BYTECODE_LIST(JUMP_IF_EQUAL)
1135 #undef JUMP_IF_EQUAL
1136 
1137  // If this is a JumpLoop, re-execute it to perform the jump to the beginning
1138  // of the loop.
1139  Label end, not_jump_loop;
1140  __ Cmp(bytecode, Operand(static_cast<int>(interpreter::Bytecode::kJumpLoop)));
1141  __ B(ne, &not_jump_loop);
1142  // We need to restore the original bytecode_offset since we might have
1143  // increased it to skip the wide / extra-wide prefix bytecode.
1144  __ Mov(bytecode_offset, original_bytecode_offset);
1145  __ B(&end);
1146 
1147  __ bind(&not_jump_loop);
1148  // Otherwise, load the size of the current bytecode and advance the offset.
1149  __ Ldrb(scratch1.W(), MemOperand(bytecode_size_table, bytecode));
1150  __ Add(bytecode_offset, bytecode_offset, scratch1);
1151 
1152  __ Bind(&end);
1153 }

1183 void Builtins::Generate_BaselineOutOfLinePrologue(MacroAssembler* masm) {
1184  UseScratchRegisterScope temps(masm);
1185  // Need a few extra registers
1186  temps.Include(CPURegList(kXRegSizeInBits, {x12, x13, x14, x15}));
1187 
1188  auto descriptor =
1189  Builtins::CallInterfaceDescriptorFor(Builtin::kBaselineOutOfLinePrologue);
1190  Register closure = descriptor.GetRegisterParameter(
1191  BaselineOutOfLinePrologueDescriptor::kClosure);
1192  // Load the feedback cell and vector from the closure.
1193  Register feedback_cell = temps.AcquireX();
1194  Register feedback_vector = temps.AcquireX();
1195  Register scratch = temps.AcquireX();
1196  __ LoadTaggedField(feedback_cell,
1197  FieldMemOperand(closure, JSFunction::kFeedbackCellOffset));
1198  __ LoadTaggedField(
1199  feedback_vector,
1200  FieldMemOperand(feedback_cell, FeedbackCell::kValueOffset));
1201  __ AssertFeedbackVector(feedback_vector, scratch);
1202 
1203 #ifndef V8_ENABLE_LEAPTIERING
1204  // Check the tiering state.
1205  Label flags_need_processing;
1206  Register flags = temps.AcquireW();
1207  __ LoadFeedbackVectorFlagsAndJumpIfNeedsProcessing(
1208  flags, feedback_vector, CodeKind::BASELINE, &flags_need_processing);
1209 #endif // !V8_ENABLE_LEAPTIERING
1210 
1211  {
1212  UseScratchRegisterScope temps(masm);
1213  ResetFeedbackVectorOsrUrgency(masm, feedback_vector, temps.AcquireW());
1214  }
1215 
1216  // Increment invocation count for the function.
1217  {
1218  UseScratchRegisterScope temps(masm);
1219  Register invocation_count = temps.AcquireW();
1220  __ Ldr(invocation_count,
1221  FieldMemOperand(feedback_vector,
1222  FeedbackVector::kInvocationCountOffset));
1223  __ Add(invocation_count, invocation_count, Operand(1));
1224  __ Str(invocation_count,
1225  FieldMemOperand(feedback_vector,
1226  FeedbackVector::kInvocationCountOffset));
1227  }
1228 
1229  FrameScope frame_scope(masm, StackFrame::MANUAL);
1230  {
1231  ASM_CODE_COMMENT_STRING(masm, "Frame Setup");
1232  // Normally the first thing we'd do here is Push(lr, fp), but we already
1233  // entered the frame in BaselineCompiler::Prologue, as we had to use the
1234  // value lr before the call to this BaselineOutOfLinePrologue builtin.
1235 
1236  Register callee_context = descriptor.GetRegisterParameter(
1237  BaselineOutOfLinePrologueDescriptor::kCalleeContext);
1238  Register callee_js_function = descriptor.GetRegisterParameter(
1239  BaselineOutOfLinePrologueDescriptor::kClosure);
1240  {
1241  UseScratchRegisterScope temps(masm);
1242  ResetJSFunctionAge(masm, callee_js_function, temps.AcquireX());
1243  }
1244  __ Push(callee_context, callee_js_function);
1245  DCHECK_EQ(callee_js_function, kJavaScriptCallTargetRegister);
1246  DCHECK_EQ(callee_js_function, kJSFunctionRegister);
1247 
1248  Register argc = descriptor.GetRegisterParameter(
1249  BaselineOutOfLinePrologueDescriptor::kJavaScriptCallArgCount);
1250  // We'll use the bytecode for both code age/OSR resetting, and pushing onto
1251  // the frame, so load it into a register.
1252  Register bytecode_array = descriptor.GetRegisterParameter(
1253  BaselineOutOfLinePrologueDescriptor::kInterpreterBytecodeArray);
1254  __ Push(argc, bytecode_array, feedback_cell, feedback_vector);
1255  __ AssertFeedbackVector(feedback_vector, scratch);
1256  }
1257 
1258  Label call_stack_guard;
1259  Register frame_size = descriptor.GetRegisterParameter(
1260  BaselineOutOfLinePrologueDescriptor::kStackFrameSize);
1261  {
1262  ASM_CODE_COMMENT_STRING(masm, "Stack/interrupt check");
1263  // Stack check. This folds the checks for both the interrupt stack limit
1264  // check and the real stack limit into one by just checking for the
1265  // interrupt limit. The interrupt limit is either equal to the real stack
1266  // limit or tighter. By ensuring we have space until that limit after
1267  // building the frame we can quickly precheck both at once.
1268  UseScratchRegisterScope temps(masm);
1269 
1270  Register sp_minus_frame_size = temps.AcquireX();
1271  __ Sub(sp_minus_frame_size, sp, frame_size);
1272  Register interrupt_limit = temps.AcquireX();
1273  __ LoadStackLimit(interrupt_limit, StackLimitKind::kInterruptStackLimit);
1274  __ Cmp(sp_minus_frame_size, interrupt_limit);
1275  __ B(lo, &call_stack_guard);
1276  }
1277 
1278  // Do "fast" return to the caller pc in lr.
1279  __ LoadRoot(kInterpreterAccumulatorRegister, RootIndex::kUndefinedValue);
1280  __ Ret();
1281 
1282 #ifndef V8_ENABLE_LEAPTIERING
1283  __ bind(&flags_need_processing);
1284  {
1285  ASM_CODE_COMMENT_STRING(masm, "Optimized marker check");
1286  // Drop the frame created by the baseline call.
1287  __ Pop<MacroAssembler::kAuthLR>(fp, lr);
1288  __ OptimizeCodeOrTailCallOptimizedCodeSlot(flags, feedback_vector);
1289  __ Trap();
1290  }
1291 #endif // !V8_ENABLE_LEAPTIERING
1292 
1293  __ bind(&call_stack_guard);
1294  {
1295  ASM_CODE_COMMENT_STRING(masm, "Stack/interrupt call");
1296  Register new_target = descriptor.GetRegisterParameter(
1297  BaselineOutOfLinePrologueDescriptor::kJavaScriptCallNewTarget);
1298 
1299  FrameScope frame_scope(masm, StackFrame::INTERNAL);
1300  // Save incoming new target or generator
1301  Register maybe_dispatch_handle = V8_JS_LINKAGE_INCLUDES_DISPATCH_HANDLE_BOOL
1302  ? kJavaScriptCallDispatchHandleRegister
1303  : padreg;
1304  // No need to SmiTag as dispatch handles always look like Smis.
1305  static_assert(kJSDispatchHandleShift > 0);
1306  __ AssertSmi(maybe_dispatch_handle);
1307  __ Push(maybe_dispatch_handle, new_target);
1308  __ SmiTag(frame_size);
1309  __ PushArgument(frame_size);
1310  __ CallRuntime(Runtime::kStackGuardWithGap);
1311  __ Pop(new_target, maybe_dispatch_handle);
1312  }
1313  __ LoadRoot(kInterpreterAccumulatorRegister, RootIndex::kUndefinedValue);
1314  __ Ret();
1315 }

1317 // static
1318 void Builtins::Generate_BaselineOutOfLinePrologueDeopt(MacroAssembler* masm) {
1319  // We're here because we got deopted during BaselineOutOfLinePrologue's stack
1320  // check. Undo all its frame creation and call into the interpreter instead.
1321 
1322  // Drop the feedback vector and the bytecode offset (was the feedback vector
1323  // but got replaced during deopt).
1324  __ Drop(2);
1325 
1326  // Bytecode array, argc, Closure, Context.
1327  __ Pop(padreg, kJavaScriptCallArgCountRegister, kJavaScriptCallTargetRegister,
1328  kContextRegister);
1329 
1330  // Drop frame pointer
1331  __ LeaveFrame(StackFrame::BASELINE);
1332 
1333  // Enter the interpreter.
1334  __ TailCallBuiltin(Builtin::kInterpreterEntryTrampoline);
1335 }
1336 
1337 // Generate code for entering a JS function with the interpreter.
1338 // On entry to the function the receiver and arguments have been pushed on the
1339 // stack left to right.
1340 //
1341 // The live registers are:
1342 // - x0: actual argument count
1343 // - x1: the JS function object being called.
1344 // - x3: the incoming new target or generator object
1345 // - x4: the dispatch handle through which we were called
1346 // - cp: our context.
1347 // - fp: our caller's frame pointer.
1348 // - lr: return address.
1349 //
1350 // The function builds an interpreter frame. See InterpreterFrameConstants in
1351 // frame-constants.h for its layout.
1352 void Builtins::Generate_InterpreterEntryTrampoline(
1353  MacroAssembler* masm, InterpreterEntryTrampolineMode mode) {
1354  Register closure = x1;
1355 
1356  // Get the bytecode array from the function object and load it into
1357  // kInterpreterBytecodeArrayRegister.
1358  Register sfi = x5;
1359  __ LoadTaggedField(
1360  sfi, FieldMemOperand(closure, JSFunction::kSharedFunctionInfoOffset));
1361  ResetSharedFunctionInfoAge(masm, sfi);
1362 
1363  // The bytecode array could have been flushed from the shared function info,
1364  // if so, call into CompileLazy.
1365  Label is_baseline, compile_lazy;
1366  GetSharedFunctionInfoBytecodeOrBaseline(masm, sfi,
1367  kInterpreterBytecodeArrayRegister,
1368  x11, &is_baseline, &compile_lazy);
1369 
1370 #ifdef V8_ENABLE_SANDBOX
1371  // Validate the parameter count. This protects against an attacker swapping
1372  // the bytecode (or the dispatch handle) such that the parameter count of the
1373  // dispatch entry doesn't match the one of the BytecodeArray.
1374  // TODO(saelo): instead of this validation step, it would probably be nicer
1375  // if we could store the BytecodeArray directly in the dispatch entry and
1376  // load it from there. Then we can easily guarantee that the parameter count
1377  // of the entry matches the parameter count of the bytecode.
1378  static_assert(V8_JS_LINKAGE_INCLUDES_DISPATCH_HANDLE_BOOL);
1379  Register dispatch_handle = kJavaScriptCallDispatchHandleRegister;
1380  __ LoadParameterCountFromJSDispatchTable(x6, dispatch_handle, x7);
1381  __ Ldrh(x7, FieldMemOperand(kInterpreterBytecodeArrayRegister,
1382  BytecodeArray::kParameterSizeOffset));
1383  __ Cmp(x6, x7);
1384  __ SbxCheck(eq, AbortReason::kJSSignatureMismatch);
1385 #endif // V8_ENABLE_SANDBOX
1386 
1387  Label push_stack_frame;
1388  Register feedback_vector = x2;
1389  __ LoadFeedbackVector(feedback_vector, closure, x7, &push_stack_frame);
1390 
1391 #ifndef V8_JITLESS
1392 #ifndef V8_ENABLE_LEAPTIERING
1393  // If feedback vector is valid, check for optimized code and update invocation
1394  // count.
1395  Label flags_need_processing;
1396  Register flags = w7;
1397  __ LoadFeedbackVectorFlagsAndJumpIfNeedsProcessing(
1398  flags, feedback_vector, CodeKind::INTERPRETED_FUNCTION,
1399  &flags_need_processing);
1400 #endif // !V8_ENABLE_LEAPTIERING
1401 
1402  ResetFeedbackVectorOsrUrgency(masm, feedback_vector, w7);
1403 
1404  // Increment invocation count for the function.
1405  __ Ldr(w10, FieldMemOperand(feedback_vector,
1406  FeedbackVector::kInvocationCountOffset));
1407  __ Add(w10, w10, Operand(1));
1408  __ Str(w10, FieldMemOperand(feedback_vector,
1409  FeedbackVector::kInvocationCountOffset));
1410 
1411  // Open a frame scope to indicate that there is a frame on the stack. The
1412  // MANUAL indicates that the scope shouldn't actually generate code to set up
1413  // the frame (that is done below).
1414 #else
1415  // Note: By omitting the above code in jitless mode we also disable:
1416  // - kFlagsLogNextExecution: only used for logging/profiling; and
1417  // - kInvocationCountOffset: only used for tiering heuristics and code
1418  // coverage.
1419 #endif // !V8_JITLESS
1420 
1421  __ Bind(&push_stack_frame);
1422  FrameScope frame_scope(masm, StackFrame::MANUAL);
1423  __ Push<MacroAssembler::kSignLR>(lr, fp);
1424  __ mov(fp, sp);
1425  __ Push(cp, closure);
1426 
1427  // Load the initial bytecode offset.
1428  __ Mov(kInterpreterBytecodeOffsetRegister,
1429  Operand(BytecodeArray::kHeaderSize - kHeapObjectTag));
1430 
1431  // Push actual argument count, bytecode array, Smi tagged bytecode array
1432  // offset and the feedback vector.
1433  __ SmiTag(x6, kInterpreterBytecodeOffsetRegister);
1434  __ Push(kJavaScriptCallArgCountRegister, kInterpreterBytecodeArrayRegister);
1435  __ Push(x6, feedback_vector);
1436 
1437  // Allocate the local and temporary register file on the stack.
1438  Label stack_overflow;
1439  {
1440  // Load frame size from the BytecodeArray object.
1441  __ Ldr(w11, FieldMemOperand(kInterpreterBytecodeArrayRegister,
1442  BytecodeArray::kFrameSizeOffset));
1443  __ Ldrh(w12, FieldMemOperand(kInterpreterBytecodeArrayRegister,
1444  BytecodeArray::kMaxArgumentsOffset));
1445  __ Add(w12, w11, Operand(w12, LSL, kSystemPointerSizeLog2));
1446 
1447  // Do a stack check to ensure we don't go over the limit.
1448  __ Sub(x10, sp, Operand(x12));
1449  {
1450  UseScratchRegisterScope temps(masm);
1451  Register scratch = temps.AcquireX();
1452  __ LoadStackLimit(scratch, StackLimitKind::kRealStackLimit);
1453  __ Cmp(x10, scratch);
1454  }
1455  __ B(lo, &stack_overflow);
1456 
1457  // If ok, push undefined as the initial value for all register file entries.
1458  // Note: there should always be at least one stack slot for the return
1459  // register in the register file.
1460  Label loop_header;
1461  __ Lsr(x11, x11, kSystemPointerSizeLog2);
1462  // Round up the number of registers to a multiple of 2, to align the stack
1463  // to 16 bytes.
1464  __ Add(x11, x11, 1);
1465  __ Bic(x11, x11, 1);
1466  __ LoadRoot(kInterpreterAccumulatorRegister, RootIndex::kUndefinedValue);
1467  __ PushMultipleTimes(kInterpreterAccumulatorRegister, x11);
1468  __ Bind(&loop_header);
1469  }
1470 
1471  // If the bytecode array has a valid incoming new target or generator object
1472  // register, initialize it with incoming value which was passed in x3.
1473  Label no_incoming_new_target_or_generator_register;
1474  __ Ldrsw(x10,
1475  FieldMemOperand(
1476  kInterpreterBytecodeArrayRegister,
1477  BytecodeArray::kIncomingNewTargetOrGeneratorRegisterOffset));
1478  __ Cbz(x10, &no_incoming_new_target_or_generator_register);
1479  __ Str(x3, MemOperand(fp, x10, LSL, kSystemPointerSizeLog2));
1480  __ Bind(&no_incoming_new_target_or_generator_register);
1481 
1482  // Perform interrupt stack check.
1483  // TODO(solanes): Merge with the real stack limit check above.
1484  Label stack_check_interrupt, after_stack_check_interrupt;
1485  __ LoadStackLimit(x10, StackLimitKind::kInterruptStackLimit);
1486  __ Cmp(sp, x10);
1487  __ B(lo, &stack_check_interrupt);
1488  __ Bind(&after_stack_check_interrupt);
1489 
1490  // The accumulator is already loaded with undefined.
1491 
1492  // Load the dispatch table into a register and dispatch to the bytecode
1493  // handler at the current bytecode offset.
1494  Label do_dispatch;
1495  __ bind(&do_dispatch);
1496  __ Mov(
1497  kInterpreterDispatchTableRegister,
1498  ExternalReference::interpreter_dispatch_table_address(masm->isolate()));
1499  __ Ldrb(x23, MemOperand(kInterpreterBytecodeArrayRegister,
1500  kInterpreterBytecodeOffsetRegister));
1501  __ Mov(x1, Operand(x23, LSL, kSystemPointerSizeLog2));
1502  __ Ldr(kJavaScriptCallCodeStartRegister,
1503  MemOperand(kInterpreterDispatchTableRegister, x1));
1504  __ Call(kJavaScriptCallCodeStartRegister);
1505 
1506  __ RecordComment("--- InterpreterEntryReturnPC point ---");
1507  if (mode == InterpreterEntryTrampolineMode::kDefault) {
1508  masm->isolate()->heap()->SetInterpreterEntryReturnPCOffset(
1509  masm->pc_offset());
1510  } else {
1511  DCHECK_EQ(mode, InterpreterEntryTrampolineMode::kForProfiling);
1512  // Both versions must be the same up to this point otherwise the builtins
1513  // will not be interchangable.
1514  CHECK_EQ(
1515  masm->isolate()->heap()->interpreter_entry_return_pc_offset().value(),
1516  masm->pc_offset());
1517  }
1518 
1519  // Any returns to the entry trampoline are either due to the return bytecode
1520  // or the interpreter tail calling a builtin and then a dispatch.
1521 
1522  __ JumpTarget();
1523 
1524  // Get bytecode array and bytecode offset from the stack frame.
1525  __ Ldr(kInterpreterBytecodeArrayRegister,
1526  MemOperand(fp, InterpreterFrameConstants::kBytecodeArrayFromFp));
1527  __ SmiUntag(kInterpreterBytecodeOffsetRegister,
1528  MemOperand(fp, InterpreterFrameConstants::kBytecodeOffsetFromFp));
1529 
1530  // Either return, or advance to the next bytecode and dispatch.
1531  Label do_return;
1532  __ Ldrb(x1, MemOperand(kInterpreterBytecodeArrayRegister,
1533  kInterpreterBytecodeOffsetRegister));
1534  AdvanceBytecodeOffsetOrReturn(masm, kInterpreterBytecodeArrayRegister,
1535  kInterpreterBytecodeOffsetRegister, x1, x2, x3,
1536  &do_return);
1537  __ B(&do_dispatch);
1538 
1539  __ bind(&do_return);
1540  // The return value is in x0.
1541  LeaveInterpreterFrame(masm, x2, x5);
1542  __ Ret();
1543 
1544  __ bind(&stack_check_interrupt);
1545  // Modify the bytecode offset in the stack to be kFunctionEntryBytecodeOffset
1546  // for the call to the StackGuard.
1547  __ Mov(kInterpreterBytecodeOffsetRegister,
1548  Operand(Smi::FromInt(BytecodeArray::kHeaderSize - kHeapObjectTag +
1549  kFunctionEntryBytecodeOffset)));
1550  __ Str(kInterpreterBytecodeOffsetRegister,
1551  MemOperand(fp, InterpreterFrameConstants::kBytecodeOffsetFromFp));
1552  __ CallRuntime(Runtime::kStackGuard);
1553 
1554  // After the call, restore the bytecode array, bytecode offset and accumulator
1555  // registers again. Also, restore the bytecode offset in the stack to its
1556  // previous value.
1557  __ Ldr(kInterpreterBytecodeArrayRegister,
1558  MemOperand(fp, InterpreterFrameConstants::kBytecodeArrayFromFp));
1559  __ Mov(kInterpreterBytecodeOffsetRegister,
1560  Operand(BytecodeArray::kHeaderSize - kHeapObjectTag));
1561  __ LoadRoot(kInterpreterAccumulatorRegister, RootIndex::kUndefinedValue);
1562 
1563  __ SmiTag(x10, kInterpreterBytecodeOffsetRegister);
1564  __ Str(x10, MemOperand(fp, InterpreterFrameConstants::kBytecodeOffsetFromFp));
1565 
1566  __ jmp(&after_stack_check_interrupt);
1567 
1568 #ifndef V8_JITLESS
1569 #ifndef V8_ENABLE_LEAPTIERING
1570  __ bind(&flags_need_processing);
1571  __ OptimizeCodeOrTailCallOptimizedCodeSlot(flags, feedback_vector);
1572 #endif // !V8_ENABLE_LEAPTIERING
1573 
1574  __ bind(&is_baseline);
1575  {
1576 #ifndef V8_ENABLE_LEAPTIERING
1577  // Load the feedback vector from the closure.
1578  __ LoadTaggedField(
1579  feedback_vector,
1580  FieldMemOperand(closure, JSFunction::kFeedbackCellOffset));
1581  __ LoadTaggedField(
1582  feedback_vector,
1583  FieldMemOperand(feedback_vector, FeedbackCell::kValueOffset));
1584 
1585  Label install_baseline_code;
1586  // Check if feedback vector is valid. If not, call prepare for baseline to
1587  // allocate it.
1588  __ LoadTaggedField(
1589  x7, FieldMemOperand(feedback_vector, HeapObject::kMapOffset));
1590  __ Ldrh(x7, FieldMemOperand(x7, Map::kInstanceTypeOffset));
1591  __ Cmp(x7, FEEDBACK_VECTOR_TYPE);
1592  __ B(ne, &install_baseline_code);
1593 
1594  // Check the tiering state.
1595  __ LoadFeedbackVectorFlagsAndJumpIfNeedsProcessing(
1596  flags, feedback_vector, CodeKind::BASELINE, &flags_need_processing);
1597 
1598  // TODO(olivf, 42204201): This fastcase is difficult to support with the
1599  // sandbox as it requires getting write access to the dispatch table. See
1600  // `JSFunction::UpdateCode`. We might want to remove it for all
1601  // configurations as it does not seem to be performance sensitive.
1602 
1603  // Load the baseline code into the closure.
1604  __ Move(x2, kInterpreterBytecodeArrayRegister);
1605  static_assert(kJavaScriptCallCodeStartRegister == x2, "ABI mismatch");
1606  __ ReplaceClosureCodeWithOptimizedCode(x2, closure);
1607  __ JumpCodeObject(x2, kJSEntrypointTag);
1608 
1609  __ bind(&install_baseline_code);
1610 #endif // !V8_ENABLE_LEAPTIERING
1611 
1612  __ GenerateTailCallToReturnedCode(Runtime::kInstallBaselineCode);
1613  }
1614 #endif // !V8_JITLESS
1615 
1616  __ bind(&compile_lazy);
1617  __ GenerateTailCallToReturnedCode(Runtime::kCompileLazy);
1618  __ Unreachable(); // Should not return.
1619 
1620  __ bind(&stack_overflow);
1621  __ CallRuntime(Runtime::kThrowStackOverflow);
1622  __ Unreachable(); // Should not return.
1623 }
1624 
1625 static void GenerateInterpreterPushArgs(MacroAssembler* masm, Register num_args,
1626  Register first_arg_index,
1627  Register spread_arg_out,
1628  ConvertReceiverMode receiver_mode,
1629  InterpreterPushArgsMode mode) {
1630  ASM_CODE_COMMENT(masm);
1631  Register last_arg_addr = x10;
1632  Register stack_addr = x11;
1633  Register slots_to_claim = x12;
1634  Register slots_to_copy = x13;
1635 
1636  DCHECK(!AreAliased(num_args, first_arg_index, last_arg_addr, stack_addr,
1637  slots_to_claim, slots_to_copy));
1638  // spread_arg_out may alias with the first_arg_index input.
1639  DCHECK(!AreAliased(spread_arg_out, last_arg_addr, stack_addr, slots_to_claim,
1640  slots_to_copy));
1641 
1642  if (mode == InterpreterPushArgsMode::kWithFinalSpread) {
1643  // Exclude final spread from slots to claim and the number of arguments.
1644  __ Sub(num_args, num_args, 1);
1645  }
1646 
1647  // Round up to an even number of slots.
1648  __ Add(slots_to_claim, num_args, 1);
1649  __ Bic(slots_to_claim, slots_to_claim, 1);
1650 
1651  __ Claim(slots_to_claim);
1652  {
1653  // Store padding, which may be overwritten.
1654  UseScratchRegisterScope temps(masm);
1655  Register scratch = temps.AcquireX();
1656  __ Sub(scratch, slots_to_claim, 1);
1657  __ Poke(padreg, Operand(scratch, LSL, kSystemPointerSizeLog2));
1658  }
1659 
1660  const bool skip_receiver =
1661  receiver_mode == ConvertReceiverMode::kNullOrUndefined;
1662  if (skip_receiver) {
1663  __ Sub(slots_to_copy, num_args, kJSArgcReceiverSlots);
1664  } else {
1665  __ Mov(slots_to_copy, num_args);
1666  }
1667  __ SlotAddress(stack_addr, skip_receiver ? 1 : 0);
1668 
1669  __ Sub(last_arg_addr, first_arg_index,
1670  Operand(slots_to_copy, LSL, kSystemPointerSizeLog2));
1671  __ Add(last_arg_addr, last_arg_addr, kSystemPointerSize);
1672 
1673  // Load the final spread argument into spread_arg_out, if necessary.
1674  if (mode == InterpreterPushArgsMode::kWithFinalSpread) {
1675  __ Ldr(spread_arg_out, MemOperand(last_arg_addr, -kSystemPointerSize));
1676  }
1677 
1678  __ CopyDoubleWords(stack_addr, last_arg_addr, slots_to_copy,
1679  MacroAssembler::kDstLessThanSrcAndReverse);
1680 
1681  if (receiver_mode == ConvertReceiverMode::kNullOrUndefined) {
1682  // Store "undefined" as the receiver arg if we need to.
1683  Register receiver = x14;
1684  __ LoadRoot(receiver, RootIndex::kUndefinedValue);
1685  __ Poke(receiver, 0);
1686  }
1687 }
1688 
1689 // static
1690 void Builtins::Generate_InterpreterPushArgsThenCallImpl(
1691  MacroAssembler* masm, ConvertReceiverMode receiver_mode,
1692  InterpreterPushArgsMode mode) {
1693  DCHECK(mode != InterpreterPushArgsMode::kArrayFunction);
1694  // ----------- S t a t e -------------
1695  // -- x0 : the number of arguments
1696  // -- x2 : the address of the first argument to be pushed. Subsequent
1697  // arguments should be consecutive above this, in the same order as
1698  // they are to be pushed onto the stack.
1699  // -- x1 : the target to call (can be any Object).
1700  // -----------------------------------
1701 
1702  // Push the arguments. num_args may be updated according to mode.
1703  // spread_arg_out will be updated to contain the last spread argument, when
1704  // mode == InterpreterPushArgsMode::kWithFinalSpread.
1705  Register num_args = x0;
1706  Register first_arg_index = x2;
1707  Register spread_arg_out =
1708  (mode == InterpreterPushArgsMode::kWithFinalSpread) ? x2 : no_reg;
1709  GenerateInterpreterPushArgs(masm, num_args, first_arg_index, spread_arg_out,
1710  receiver_mode, mode);
1711 
1712  // Call the target.
1713  if (mode == InterpreterPushArgsMode::kWithFinalSpread) {
1714  __ TailCallBuiltin(Builtin::kCallWithSpread);
1715  } else {
1716  __ TailCallBuiltin(Builtins::Call(receiver_mode));
1717  }
1718 }

1720 // static
1721 void Builtins::Generate_InterpreterPushArgsThenConstructImpl(
1722  MacroAssembler* masm, InterpreterPushArgsMode mode) {
1723  // ----------- S t a t e -------------
1724  // -- x0 : argument count
1725  // -- x3 : new target
1726  // -- x1 : constructor to call
1727  // -- x2 : allocation site feedback if available, undefined otherwise
1728  // -- x4 : address of the first argument
1729  // -----------------------------------
1730  __ AssertUndefinedOrAllocationSite(x2);
1731 
1732  // Push the arguments. num_args may be updated according to mode.
1733  // spread_arg_out will be updated to contain the last spread argument, when
1734  // mode == InterpreterPushArgsMode::kWithFinalSpread.
1735  Register num_args = x0;
1736  Register first_arg_index = x4;
1737  Register spread_arg_out =
1738  (mode == InterpreterPushArgsMode::kWithFinalSpread) ? x2 : no_reg;
1739  GenerateInterpreterPushArgs(masm, num_args, first_arg_index, spread_arg_out,
1740  ConvertReceiverMode::kNullOrUndefined, mode);
1741 
1742  if (mode == InterpreterPushArgsMode::kArrayFunction) {
1743  __ AssertFunction(x1);
1744 
1745  // Tail call to the array construct stub (still in the caller
1746  // context at this point).
1747  __ TailCallBuiltin(Builtin::kArrayConstructorImpl);
1748  } else if (mode == InterpreterPushArgsMode::kWithFinalSpread) {
1749  // Call the constructor with x0, x1, and x3 unmodified.
1750  __ TailCallBuiltin(Builtin::kConstructWithSpread);
1751  } else {
1752  DCHECK_EQ(InterpreterPushArgsMode::kOther, mode);
1753  // Call the constructor with x0, x1, and x3 unmodified.
1754  __ TailCallBuiltin(Builtin::kConstruct);
1755  }
1756 }
1757 
1758 // static
1759 void Builtins::Generate_ConstructForwardAllArgsImpl(
1760  MacroAssembler* masm, ForwardWhichFrame which_frame) {
1761  // ----------- S t a t e -------------
1762  // -- x3 : new target
1763  // -- x1 : constructor to call
1764  // -----------------------------------
1765  Label stack_overflow;
1766 
1767  // Load the frame pointer into x4.
1768  switch (which_frame) {
1769  case ForwardWhichFrame::kCurrentFrame:
1770  __ Move(x4, fp);
1771  break;
1772  case ForwardWhichFrame::kParentFrame:
1773  __ Ldr(x4, MemOperand(fp, StandardFrameConstants::kCallerFPOffset));
1774  break;
1775  }
1776 
1777  // Load the argument count into x0.
1778  __ Ldr(x0, MemOperand(x4, StandardFrameConstants::kArgCOffset));
1779 
1780  // Point x4 to the base of the argument list to forward, excluding the
1781  // receiver.
1782  __ Add(x4, x4,
1783  Operand((StandardFrameConstants::kFixedSlotCountAboveFp + 1) *
1784  kSystemPointerSize));
1785 
1786  Register stack_addr = x11;
1787  Register slots_to_claim = x12;
1788  Register argc_without_receiver = x13;
1789 
1790  // Round up to even number of slots.
1791  __ Add(slots_to_claim, x0, 1);
1792  __ Bic(slots_to_claim, slots_to_claim, 1);
1793 
1794  __ StackOverflowCheck(slots_to_claim, &stack_overflow);
1795 
1796  // Adjust the stack pointer.
1797  __ Claim(slots_to_claim);
1798  {
1799  // Store padding, which may be overwritten.
1800  UseScratchRegisterScope temps(masm);
1801  Register scratch = temps.AcquireX();
1802  __ Sub(scratch, slots_to_claim, 1);
1803  __ Poke(padreg, Operand(scratch, LSL, kSystemPointerSizeLog2));
1804  }
1805 
1806  // Copy the arguments.
1807  __ Sub(argc_without_receiver, x0, kJSArgcReceiverSlots);
1808  __ SlotAddress(stack_addr, 1);
1809  __ CopyDoubleWords(stack_addr, x4, argc_without_receiver);
1810 
1811  // Push a slot for the receiver to be constructed.
1812  __ Mov(x14, Operand(0));
1813  __ Poke(x14, 0);
1814 
1815  // Call the constructor with x0, x1, and x3 unmodified.
1816  __ TailCallBuiltin(Builtin::kConstruct);
1817 
1818  __ Bind(&stack_overflow);
1819  {
1820  __ TailCallRuntime(Runtime::kThrowStackOverflow);
1821  __ Unreachable();
1822  }
1823 }

1827 void NewImplicitReceiver(MacroAssembler* masm) {
1828  // ----------- S t a t e -------------
1829  // -- x0 : the number of arguments
1830  // -- x1 : constructor to call (checked to be a JSFunction)
1831  // -- x3 : new target
1832  //
1833  // Stack:
1834  // -- Implicit Receiver
1835  // -- [arguments without receiver]
1836  // -- Implicit Receiver
1837  // -- Context
1838  // -- FastConstructMarker
1839  // -- FramePointer
1840  // -----------------------------------
1841  Register implicit_receiver = x4;
1842 
1843  // Save live registers.
1844  __ SmiTag(x0);
1845  __ Push(x0, x1, x3, padreg);
1846  __ CallBuiltin(Builtin::kFastNewObject);
1847  // Save result.
1848  __ Mov(implicit_receiver, x0);
1849  // Restore live registers.
1850  __ Pop(padreg, x3, x1, x0);
1851  __ SmiUntag(x0);
1852 
1853  // Patch implicit receiver (in arguments)
1854  __ Poke(implicit_receiver, 0 * kSystemPointerSize);
1855  // Patch second implicit (in construct frame)
1856  __ Str(implicit_receiver,
1857  MemOperand(fp, FastConstructFrameConstants::kImplicitReceiverOffset));
1858 
1859  // Restore context.
1860  __ Ldr(cp, MemOperand(fp, FastConstructFrameConstants::kContextOffset));
1861 }

1865 // static
1866 void Builtins::Generate_InterpreterPushArgsThenFastConstructFunction(
1867  MacroAssembler* masm) {
1868  // ----------- S t a t e -------------
1869  // -- x0 : argument count
1870  // -- x1 : constructor to call (checked to be a JSFunction)
1871  // -- x3 : new target
1872  // -- x4 : address of the first argument
1873  // -- cp : context pointer
1874  // -----------------------------------
1875  __ AssertFunction(x1);
1876 
1877  // Check if target has a [[Construct]] internal method.
1878  Label non_constructor;
1879  __ LoadMap(x2, x1);
1880  __ Ldrb(x2, FieldMemOperand(x2, Map::kBitFieldOffset));
1881  __ TestAndBranchIfAllClear(x2, Map::Bits1::IsConstructorBit::kMask,
1882  &non_constructor);
1883 
1884  // Enter a construct frame.
1885  FrameScope scope(masm, StackFrame::MANUAL);
1886  __ EnterFrame(StackFrame::FAST_CONSTRUCT);
1887 
1888  if (v8_flags.debug_code) {
1889  // Check that FrameScope pushed the context on to the stack already.
1890  __ Peek(x2, 0);
1891  __ Cmp(x2, cp);
1892  __ Check(eq, AbortReason::kUnexpectedValue);
1893  }
1894 
1895  // Implicit receiver stored in the construct frame.
1896  __ LoadRoot(x2, RootIndex::kTheHoleValue);
1897  __ Push(x2, padreg);
1898 
1899  // Push arguments + implicit receiver.
1900  GenerateInterpreterPushArgs(masm, x0, x4, Register::no_reg(),
1901  ConvertReceiverMode::kNullOrUndefined,
1902  InterpreterPushArgsMode::kOther);
1903  __ Poke(x2, 0 * kSystemPointerSize);
1904 
1905  // Check if it is a builtin call.
1906  Label builtin_call;
1907  __ LoadTaggedField(
1908  x2, FieldMemOperand(x1, JSFunction::kSharedFunctionInfoOffset));
1909  __ Ldr(w2, FieldMemOperand(x2, SharedFunctionInfo::kFlagsOffset));
1910  __ TestAndBranchIfAnySet(w2, SharedFunctionInfo::ConstructAsBuiltinBit::kMask,
1911  &builtin_call);
1912 
1913  // Check if we need to create an implicit receiver.
1914  Label not_create_implicit_receiver;
1915  __ DecodeField<SharedFunctionInfo::FunctionKindBits>(w2);
1916  __ JumpIfIsInRange(
1917  w2, static_cast<uint32_t>(FunctionKind::kDefaultDerivedConstructor),
1918  static_cast<uint32_t>(FunctionKind::kDerivedConstructor),
1919  &not_create_implicit_receiver);
1920  NewImplicitReceiver(masm);
1921  __ bind(&not_create_implicit_receiver);
1922 
1923  // Call the function.
1924  __ InvokeFunctionWithNewTarget(x1, x3, x0, InvokeType::kCall);
1925 
1926  // ----------- S t a t e -------------
1927  // -- x0 constructor result
1928  //
1929  // Stack:
1930  // -- Implicit Receiver
1931  // -- Context
1932  // -- FastConstructMarker
1933  // -- FramePointer
1934  // -----------------------------------
1935 
1936  // Store offset of return address for deoptimizer.
1937  masm->isolate()->heap()->SetConstructStubInvokeDeoptPCOffset(
1938  masm->pc_offset());
1939 
1940  // If the result is an object (in the ECMA sense), we should get rid
1941  // of the receiver and use the result; see ECMA-262 section 13.2.2-7
1942  // on page 74.
1943  Label use_receiver, do_throw, leave_and_return, check_receiver;
1944 
1945  // If the result is undefined, we jump out to using the implicit receiver.
1946  __ CompareRoot(x0, RootIndex::kUndefinedValue);
1947  __ B(ne, &check_receiver);
1948 
1949  // Throw away the result of the constructor invocation and use the
1950  // on-stack receiver as the result.
1951  __ Bind(&use_receiver);
1952  __ Ldr(x0,
1953  MemOperand(fp, FastConstructFrameConstants::kImplicitReceiverOffset));
1954  __ CompareRoot(x0, RootIndex::kTheHoleValue);
1955  __ B(eq, &do_throw);
1956 
1957  __ Bind(&leave_and_return);
1958  // Leave construct frame.
1959  __ LeaveFrame(StackFrame::FAST_CONSTRUCT);
1960  __ Ret();
1961 
1962  // Otherwise we do a smi check and fall through to check if the return value
1963  // is a valid receiver.
1964  __ bind(&check_receiver);
1965 
1966  // If the result is a smi, it is *not* an object in the ECMA sense.
1967  __ JumpIfSmi(x0, &use_receiver);
1968 
1969  // Check if the type of the result is not an object in the ECMA sense.
1970  __ JumpIfJSAnyIsNotPrimitive(x0, x4, &leave_and_return);
1971  __ B(&use_receiver);
1972 
1973  __ bind(&builtin_call);
1974  // TODO(victorgomes): Check the possibility to turn this into a tailcall.
1975  __ InvokeFunctionWithNewTarget(x1, x3, x0, InvokeType::kCall);
1976  __ LeaveFrame(StackFrame::FAST_CONSTRUCT);
1977  __ Ret();
1978 
1979  __ Bind(&do_throw);
1980  // Restore the context from the frame.
1981  __ Ldr(cp, MemOperand(fp, FastConstructFrameConstants::kContextOffset));
1982  __ CallRuntime(Runtime::kThrowConstructorReturnedNonObject);
1983  __ Unreachable();
1984 
1985  // Called Construct on an Object that doesn't have a [[Construct]] internal
1986  // method.
1987  __ bind(&non_constructor);
1988  __ TailCallBuiltin(Builtin::kConstructedNonConstructable);
1989 }

1991 static void Generate_InterpreterEnterBytecode(MacroAssembler* masm) {
1992  // Initialize the dispatch table register.
1993  __ Mov(
1994  kInterpreterDispatchTableRegister,
1995  ExternalReference::interpreter_dispatch_table_address(masm->isolate()));
1996 
1997  // Get the bytecode array pointer from the frame.
1998  __ Ldr(kInterpreterBytecodeArrayRegister,
1999  MemOperand(fp, InterpreterFrameConstants::kBytecodeArrayFromFp));
2000 
2001  if (v8_flags.debug_code) {
2002  // Check function data field is actually a BytecodeArray object.
2003  __ AssertNotSmi(
2004  kInterpreterBytecodeArrayRegister,
2005  AbortReason::kFunctionDataShouldBeBytecodeArrayOnInterpreterEntry);
2006  __ IsObjectType(kInterpreterBytecodeArrayRegister, x1, x1,
2007  BYTECODE_ARRAY_TYPE);
2008  __ Assert(
2009  eq, AbortReason::kFunctionDataShouldBeBytecodeArrayOnInterpreterEntry);
2010  }
2011 
2012  // Get the target bytecode offset from the frame.
2013  __ SmiUntag(kInterpreterBytecodeOffsetRegister,
2014  MemOperand(fp, InterpreterFrameConstants::kBytecodeOffsetFromFp));
2015 
2016  if (v8_flags.debug_code) {
2017  Label okay;
2018  __ cmp(kInterpreterBytecodeOffsetRegister,
2019  Operand(BytecodeArray::kHeaderSize - kHeapObjectTag));
2020  __ B(ge, &okay);
2021  __ Unreachable();
2022  __ bind(&okay);
2023  }
2024 
2025  // Dispatch to the target bytecode.
2026  __ Ldrb(x23, MemOperand(kInterpreterBytecodeArrayRegister,
2027  kInterpreterBytecodeOffsetRegister));
2028  __ Mov(x1, Operand(x23, LSL, kSystemPointerSizeLog2));
2029  __ Ldr(kJavaScriptCallCodeStartRegister,
2030  MemOperand(kInterpreterDispatchTableRegister, x1));
2031 
2032  {
2033  UseScratchRegisterScope temps(masm);
2034  temps.Exclude(x17);
2035  __ Mov(x17, kJavaScriptCallCodeStartRegister);
2036  __ Call(x17);
2037  }
2038 
2039  // We return here after having executed the function in the interpreter.
2040  // Now jump to the correct point in the interpreter entry trampoline.
2041  Label builtin_trampoline, trampoline_loaded;
2042  Tagged<Smi> interpreter_entry_return_pc_offset(
2043  masm->isolate()->heap()->interpreter_entry_return_pc_offset());
2044  DCHECK_NE(interpreter_entry_return_pc_offset, Smi::zero());
2045 
2046  // If the SFI function_data is an InterpreterData, the function will have a
2047  // custom copy of the interpreter entry trampoline for profiling. If so,
2048  // get the custom trampoline, otherwise grab the entry address of the global
2049  // trampoline.
2050  __ Ldr(x1, MemOperand(fp, StandardFrameConstants::kFunctionOffset));
2051  __ LoadTaggedField(
2052  x1, FieldMemOperand(x1, JSFunction::kSharedFunctionInfoOffset));
2053  __ LoadTrustedPointerField(
2054  x1, FieldMemOperand(x1, SharedFunctionInfo::kTrustedFunctionDataOffset),
2055  kUnknownIndirectPointerTag);
2056  __ IsObjectType(x1, kInterpreterDispatchTableRegister,
2057  kInterpreterDispatchTableRegister, INTERPRETER_DATA_TYPE);
2058  __ B(ne, &builtin_trampoline);
2059 
2060  __ LoadProtectedPointerField(
2061  x1, FieldMemOperand(x1, InterpreterData::kInterpreterTrampolineOffset));
2062  __ LoadCodeInstructionStart(x1, x1, kJSEntrypointTag);
2063  __ B(&trampoline_loaded);
2064 
2065  __ Bind(&builtin_trampoline);
2066  __ Mov(x1, ExternalReference::
2067  address_of_interpreter_entry_trampoline_instruction_start(
2068  masm->isolate()));
2069  __ Ldr(x1, MemOperand(x1));
2070 
2071  __ Bind(&trampoline_loaded);
2072 
2073  {
2074  UseScratchRegisterScope temps(masm);
2075  temps.Exclude(x17);
2076  __ Add(x17, x1, Operand(interpreter_entry_return_pc_offset.value()));
2077  __ Br(x17);
2078  }
2079 }

2081 void Builtins::Generate_InterpreterEnterAtNextBytecode(MacroAssembler* masm) {
2082  // Get bytecode array and bytecode offset from the stack frame.
2083  __ ldr(kInterpreterBytecodeArrayRegister,
2084  MemOperand(fp, InterpreterFrameConstants::kBytecodeArrayFromFp));
2085  __ SmiUntag(kInterpreterBytecodeOffsetRegister,
2086  MemOperand(fp, InterpreterFrameConstants::kBytecodeOffsetFromFp));
2087 
2088  Label enter_bytecode, function_entry_bytecode;
2089  __ cmp(kInterpreterBytecodeOffsetRegister,
2090  Operand(BytecodeArray::kHeaderSize - kHeapObjectTag +
2091  kFunctionEntryBytecodeOffset));
2092  __ B(eq, &function_entry_bytecode);
2093 
2094  // Load the current bytecode.
2095  __ Ldrb(x1, MemOperand(kInterpreterBytecodeArrayRegister,
2096  kInterpreterBytecodeOffsetRegister));
2097 
2098  // Advance to the next bytecode.
2099  Label if_return;
2100  AdvanceBytecodeOffsetOrReturn(masm, kInterpreterBytecodeArrayRegister,
2101  kInterpreterBytecodeOffsetRegister, x1, x2, x3,
2102  &if_return);
2103 
2104  __ bind(&enter_bytecode);
2105  // Convert new bytecode offset to a Smi and save in the stackframe.
2106  __ SmiTag(x2, kInterpreterBytecodeOffsetRegister);
2107  __ Str(x2, MemOperand(fp, InterpreterFrameConstants::kBytecodeOffsetFromFp));
2108 
2109  Generate_InterpreterEnterBytecode(masm);
2110 
2111  __ bind(&function_entry_bytecode);
2112  // If the code deoptimizes during the implicit function entry stack interrupt
2113  // check, it will have a bailout ID of kFunctionEntryBytecodeOffset, which is
2114  // not a valid bytecode offset. Detect this case and advance to the first
2115  // actual bytecode.
2116  __ Mov(kInterpreterBytecodeOffsetRegister,
2117  Operand(BytecodeArray::kHeaderSize - kHeapObjectTag));
2118  __ B(&enter_bytecode);
2119 
2120  // We should never take the if_return path.
2121  __ bind(&if_return);
2122  __ Abort(AbortReason::kInvalidBytecodeAdvance);
2123 }
